@744=~zealot of the written word~
@745=~Zealot of the Written Word~
@746=~ZEALOT OF THE WRITTEN WORD: Also sometimes called Carmendines after their (long-dead) founder. These monks are followers of Deneir. They spend their time recording information, developing their theses on various forms of unarmed combat, earning money for their church (usually by making books, paper, and ink, or working as scribes), and even accompanying clerics of the faith on quests. When traveling, a Zealot normally carries a small book or bundle of scrolls showing the next martial arts form she intends to master, all of which have complex and flowery names.

Advantages:

 	Level 3: Gains 10 lore. Gains an additional 10 lore every three levels.
 	Level 5: Can cast Clairvoyance once per day.
 	Level 7: Can cast Farsight once per day.
 	Level 13: Can cast Scribe Scrolls once per day.

SCRIBE SCROLLS

This ability allows a monk to create priest scrolls. The scrolls that the monk can create are randomly chosen from the following list:
1) Protection from Acid
2) Protection from Cold
3) Protection from Electricity
4) Protection from Fire
5) Protection from Magic
6) Protection from Poison
7) Protection from Undead
8) Raise Dead
9) Heal
10) Resurrection


Disadvantages:

- Cannot use Stunning Blow.
- Cannot use Quivering Palm.


Restrictions:

- Must be lawful good.
- Must have at least 9 intelligence.~

@747=~You spent much of your early years engrossed in the tomes found within your monasteries libraries. At the time the collection seemed endless, though as you have grown older you have realized that it featured only a small portion of the knowledge written regarding the realms.

While the rest of your order are content with remaining in the monastery to learn and protect existing holdings you have long since sought to leave in order to search the realms for other rare books and catalogue your own discoveries.

Having read of the tombs and caverns of the Spine of the World you have always wondered what lost knowledge could be found within them. Few adventurers in the north would bother to keep books and those that would likely would have simply sold the ones they had acquired rather than keeping them for themselves. 

With that in mind you've set forth for Icewind Dale, quill and parchment at your side. What mysteries and wonders lay within this frozen wasteland you do not fully know, though the adventure itself will undoubtedly be its own reward.~
@748=~A monk follower of Deneir.~


//Thief kits

//Mouseburglar

@749=~mouseburglar~
@750=~Mouseburglar~
@751=~MOUSEBURGLAR: These stealthy characters are consummate spies and sneak thieves who in some ways behave more like halflings than the average gnome thief. Striving to be as quiet as mice, they infiltrate lairs, mansions, or enemy camps. They rely upon secrecy, disguise, and silence in order to conceal their presence. Preferring very much to flee rather than fight, they consider a truly successful mission one which is concluded before the victim even learns that the gnome has been there.

Advantages:

- Can become specialized in shortbows, daggers, slings, darts, and short swords.

- Level 1: Gains +5% towards Move Silently. This repeats every 3 levels up to a maximum of +50% at level 28.
- Level 2: Gains +5% towards Hide in Shadows. This repeats every 3 levels up to a maximum of +50% at level 29.
- Level 3: Gains +5% towards Find Traps. This repeats every 3 levels up to a maximum of +50% at level 30.


Disadvantages:

- Gets -1 to their Thac0 when using melee weapons.
- Cannot become proficient in crossbows.

Restrictions:

- Must be a gnome.
- Must have at least 13 dexterity and 13 intelligence.~

@752=~You grew up on the streets of Athkatla, earning your living in whatever way was necessary. As an orphan few cared about what business you got yourself into and few amongst those that did could have stopped you anyways.

In time you gained a particular affinity for picking out targets and stealing valuable merchandise. As you've grown older you are now less quick on your feet, but far more experienced, and as a result you almost always remain unnoticed by your target. Today there are few treasures in the city that could elude your grasp.

Your most recent job was a critical success. The diamond that you stole was surely worth a small fortune and the employers that you stole it for could not be happier with their latest acquisition.

As you gently slid down the rafters and quietly fell onto the cobblestone beneath your living quarters you couldn't help but feel gratified at your recent success. Your target, a wealthy businessman, was none the wiser about your activities.

Still, you have felt recently that you could be something much greater than you are now. Hearing tales of the great treasures to be found in the north, and having no interest in remaining in Athkatla, you have set your sights on travelling to Icewind Dale. You hope that upon arrival in one of the Ten Towns you will learn more about what opportunities await you in this unforgiving wasteland.~
@753=~A gnome thief who excels at stealing things and not getting caught.~

//Pest Controller
@754=~pest controller~
@755=~Pest Controller~
@756=~PEST CONTROLLER: Though there are dwarven thieves in the realms that engage in practices of theft, many dwarf thieves actually seek to improve their mechanical knowledge instead of their sleight of hand. Pest controllers for instance are experts at removing rats, carrion crawlers, ettercaps, spiders, beetles, kobolds, goblins, and other pests from strongholds and homes. They typically work as part of larger guilds, taking on apprentices as needed. They are also experts on improving an areas defensibility by laying elaborate traps, and are often hired for such a purpose.


Advantages:

- You gain access to an additional use of Set Snare every four levels instead of every five levels.
- Starts with +5 towards Move Silently, +5 towards Find Traps, and +10 towards Set Traps.
- Level 1: You gain access to Pest Snare. You can additional uses of this every 5 levels.

PEST SNARE

Over numerous centuries Pest Controllers have passed on the technique for making these traps to their apprentices. Like traditional traps this trap is designed so that it can strike a target from a distance. However, its teeth and mechanisms make it harmless against larger creatures. Its damage and effects vary by your characters level.

Level 1: 5 missile and 10 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures.
Level 11: 10 missile and 20 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures.
Level 16: 10 missile and 25 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures. Will slow any target affected by it for three rounds.
Level 21: 15 missile and 25 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures. Will slay a target affected by it if they fail a save vs death (with a +2 bonus). Creatures that survive are slowed for three rounds.



Disadvantages:

- May only distribute 15 points each level towards thieving skills.
- Starts with -10 towards Pick Pocket.

Restrictions:

- Cannot have higher than 14 charisma.~

@757=~You grew up in a dilapidated part of the human city of Waterdeep. For many years you gained your greatest degree of education from what broken trinkets the humans of your city had thrown aside. Whether that was children toys, mechanical parts, and even the odd broken trap or two. From these you gained an understanding of mechanics, a knowledge that proved to be quite handy given your current career.

At the age of 18 you signed up at the local Pest Controllers guild, hoping by doing so that you would earn some extra coin to help your struggling family. Dwarven Pest Controllers are simply the finest craftsman for handling pests, be they goblins, carrion crawlers, or even giant spiders. They are also frequently hired by wealthy lords and noblemen looking to secure their holds against invaders. 

Since joining your guild you have proven yourself to be a natural at the craft. Guided by your master you have gained a greater understanding of what your profession involves.

Seeing your potential himself your master has decided that you need real world experience before you can progress farther in your guild. Having himself heard tales of the great monsters and beasts of the north your master has tasked you with travelling to that desolate region. There you shall test your abilities and master your craft. ~
@758=~An expert trap layer~

@759=~Pest Snare~
@760=~Pest Snare

Over numerous centuries Pest Controllers have passed on the technique for making these traps to their apprentices. Like traditional traps this trap is designed so that it can strike a target from a distance. However, its teeth and mechanisms make it harmless against larger creatures. Its damage and effects vary by your characters level.

Level 1: 5 missile and 10 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures.
Level 11: 10 missile and 20 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures.
Level 16: 10 missile and 25 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures. Will slow any target affected by it for three rounds.
Level 21: 15 missile and 25 crushing damage to small and medium sized creatures. Will slay a target affected by it if they fail a save vs death (with a +2 bonus). Creatures that survive are slowed for three rounds.~


@761=~scout~
@762=~Scout~
@763=~SCOUT: A Scout is a thief, usually solitary, who operates in a wilderness setting. Besides working as a guide, spy, or saboteur for hire in the wilderness, many Scouts are involved in such illicit activities as poaching. Though they lack the "silly ethics" of the ranger class they are not prohibited from being good, and in many ways they are more dependable than thieves in general. In fact their rugged individualism and harsh judgment often endears them to adventurers.

Advantages:

- They get +15 to Hide in Shadows and Move Silently.
- Once per round Scouts can attempt to make a Surprise Attack against an opponent.

SURPRISE ATTACK

Once per round Scouts can attempt to make a surprise attack against an opponent. They only have a 1/6 chance of successfully positioning themselves to make this surprise attack. If they are successful they are granted an additional +4 Thac0 and an additional attack per round for the next round (success is represented by a Called Shot icon). There are no penalties for not being successful.

- Level 3: They can track like rangers.

Disadvantages:

- The get -5 to Open Locks, Find Traps, Detect Illusion, Set Traps, and Pickpocket.
- They can only distribute 20 points each level.~

@764=~You lived most of your life as a wanderer, moving from village to village, forest to forest as needed. The result of this was that you spent much of your earlier years playing in the wilderness, a fact that has helped you adapt yourself to the environments around you.

Versatility is your strong suit. Today you might serve as a scout for an advancing army, while tomorrow you may serve as a saboteur fighting back. You take work as needed, with only your personal moral compass to guide you on whom you will serve and the acts you agree to commit. You are however a rogue by nature. Illicit activity is second nature to you, regardless of whatever form that might take.

In your travels you have heard much about the north. Having heard stories of the challenges and trials of those who have travelled there you have become increasingly curious about the region. Staff in hand you now travel to Icewind Dale, a remote region of the north, hoping to see for yourself the challenges it offers adventurers.~
@765=~A thief that scouts and frequently lives in the wilderness.~

@766=~Surprise Attack~
@767=~Surprise Attack

Once per round Scouts can attempt to make a surprise attack against an opponent. They only have a 1/6 chance of successfully positioning themselves to make this surprise attack. If they are successful they are granted an additional +4 Thac0 and an additional attack per round for the next round (success is represented by a Called Shot icon). There are no penalties for not being successful.~


@768=~tumbler~
@769=~Tumbler~
@770=~TUMBLER: The Tumbler is a gnome who employs creative and vigorous means to get into places, meanwhile performing tricks and feats for the edification of his or her fellow villagers. Adept at climbing and falling, the Tumbler can walk a rope stretched between two high points, scale a sheer surface, and bob and evade his or her way through deadly combat--often rolling right between a larger opponent's legs!

Advantages:

- Level 1: Can use Tumble once per day. Gains additional uses of this ability once every three levels.

TUMBLE

When activated the Tumbler gains a -6 AC bonus for the next round. This cannot be used in conjunction with Climb Walls.

- Level 3: Can use Climb Walls once per day. Gains additional uses of this ability once every four levels.

CLIMB WALLS

The Tumbler can climb walls or any vertical structure or rock formation in an effort to avoid an enemy. For the first round the ability is active the Tumbler is unable to attack, as they are instead looking for a ledge to attack back from. During the five rounds this ability is active the Tumbler's AC is improved by 4 and ranged attacks made by them get a bonus of -4 Thac0. This cannot be used in conjunction with Tumble.

Disadvantages:

- They start with a 15 point penalty to their Open Locks skill.

Restrictions:

- Must be a gnome
- Must have a dexterity of at least 14.~

@771=~You learned the art of tumbling early in life. As a child you were often running around and avoiding the bullying efforts of your peers. Climbing walls and avoidance became necessary for your existence, and since then you have only improved with these talents.

Years of practice lead you to an interest in acrobatics. When a travelling circus came to town you took this as a chance to show them what you were made of, and though you were still young at the time the circus took you in and expanded on your teachings.

You have since moved away from working in the circus, though you remember your time there fondly. It was only recently that you were spending much of your time engaging in acts of petty thievery. Thievings guilds in larger cities pay handsomely for thieves who show remarkable talent at climbing walls, a fact that attracted you to your current profession. You have since become a fairly capable thief, though you admit you still have much to learn about the art.

Ideally you would have preferred to improve your thieving abilities while stealing from valuable targets, however your guild leader apparently had something else in mind. Rumours swirl about hidden treasures in Icewind Dale, a far away and remote northern region of Faerun.

You have been tasked by your guild leader to travel to this region. What you will find there you are unsure, though you do look forward to testing your abilities against whatever you do encounter.~
@772=~a thief who can climb walls and tumble~

@773=~Tumble~
@774=~When activated the Tumbler gains a -6 AC bonus for the next round. This cannot be used in conjunction with Climb Walls.~

@775=~Climb Walls~
@776=~Climb Walls

The Tumbler can climb walls or any vertical structure or rock formation in an effort to avoid an enemy. For the first round the ability is active the Tumbler is unable to attack, as they are instead looking for a ledge to attack back from. During the five rounds this ability is active the Tumbler's AC is improved by 4 and ranged attacks made by them get a bonus of -4 Thac0. This cannot be used in conjunction with Tumble.~


@777=~vermin slayer~
@778=~Vermin Slayer~
@779=~VERMIN SLAYER: The Vermin Slayer is a highly skilled specialist who enters the tunnel systems of monsters such as kobolds and goblins with the intention of eradicating them. Vermin Slayers are also adept at negotiating the constricted passages created by giant rats, centipedes, and other pests and vermin. They are used to fighting in confined spaces and are experts at hiding in shadows, where they wait to surprise their prey. Vermin Slayers are similar to Pest Controllers, but where a Pest Controller uses traps to catch his prey, Vermin Slayers actively hunt victims with light crossbows and other assorted weapons.

Advantages:

- Can specialize in any weapon or weapon style (*** for Two-Weapon Style), receives specialisation bonuses like a fighter would, gets level attack per round bonuses like a fighter (at levels 7 and 13), and gets only a +2 penalty to Thac0 when using a weapon without proficiency.
- Gets +1 Thac0 and +2 damage when attacking carrion crawlers, spiders, beetles, kobolds, and goblins.
- Gets +5% Hide in Shadows, +5% Move Silently, and +5% Find Traps 
- Level 2: Gets a +1 bonus to Thac0. Gets this bonus every 2 levels, to a maximum of +5 Thac0 at level 10.
- Gets hit dice of 1d8. After level 10 it gains 3 hit points a level.

Disadvantages:

- Gets -10 to pickpocket
- Can only distribute 15 thief points every level.
- You only get access to a new use of Set Snare every 6 levels (levels 1, 7, 13, etc).
- Backstab multiplier, sneak attacks, and critical strikes progress more slowly than an unkitted Thief:

Backstab multiplier
  Level 1-6: x2
  Level 7-10: x3
  Level 11-14: x4
  Level 15+: x5

Sneak attacks (if 3E Sneak Attack is enabled):
  Level 1-5: +1d6
  Level 6-9: +2d6
  Level 10-13: +3d6
  Level 14-17: +4d6
  Level 18-21: +5d6
  Level 22-25: +6d6
  Level 26-29: +7d6
  Level 30: +8d6


Crippling strikes (if 3E Sneak Attack is enabled):
  Level 7-10: -1 to target's hit and damage rolls
  Level 11-14: -2 to target's hit and damage rolls
  Level 15-18: -3 to target's hit and damage rolls
  Level 19-22: -4 to target's hit and damage rolls
  Level 23-26: -5 to target's hit and damage rolls
  Level 27-30: -6 to target's hit and damage rolls


Restrictions:

- Must be a dwarf.
- Must have at least 14 strength and 14 dexterity.~

@780=~You grew up in a small dwarven community found deep within a mountainside. In the years you spent there the constant encounters you had with giant spiders, goblins, and other creatures instilled in you a strong understanding of the threat these creatures can pose. As you grew older you began to realize that your burgeoning skills in combat could be more useful elsewhere.

You set forth for the surface and travelled to the city of Waterdeep. There you joined a local guild dedicated to removing pests from the property of their clients. As a member of this guild you gained the respect and admiration of your peers, even if you often found yourself lacking their resourcefulness as thieves.

Your efforts at improving your own thieves skills have been long and marginally rewarding. Seeing your potential however the leader of your guild recently called for you.

You were tasked with travelling to Icewind Dale, a region of Faerun located far to the north from your present location in Waterdeep. Your guild leader has viewed events transpiring there as an opportunity to expand their influence. While you understand the petty concerns of your guild what really excites you about this journey is the opportunity to test your own capabilities in battle. You now travel to the village of Easthaven, staff in hand, hoping to make a name for yourself in this brutal climate.~
@781=~Dwarf thief who fights vermin and pests~


//Paladin and Cleric kits

//Knight of the Mystic Fire (Divinate of Mystra)

@115=~knight of the mystic fire~
@116=~Knight of the Mystic Fire~
@117=~KNIGHT OF THE MYSTIC FIRE: The Knights of the Mystic Fire are an order of knights that work in the service of Mystra, the Lady of Spells. Mystra herself seeks to preserve the stability of the Weave, and has tasked her clergy and paladins to act with this in mind. As those who represent some of her most faithful warriors the Knights of the Mystic Fire are frequently sent out throughout the realms to investigate magic users as needed.

Advantages

- Level 1: Gets +2 to their Save vs Spells.
- Level 5: They gain the ability to cast Dispel Magic as an innate ability once per day.
- Level 6: They can cast Magic Missiles as a 1st level priest spell.
- Level 9: Their casting times are reduced by 3.
- Level 12: They can cast Minor Sequencer as a 3rd level cleric spell.


Disadvantages

- Cannot use Cure Disease, Protection from Evil, or Smite Evil
- Does not gain Divine Courage

Restrictions

- Must be Lawful Neutral~

@118=~As a the child of mages magic has always played a significant role in your life. At a young age your father in particular took an active interest in teaching it to you, though after much effort it never really sunk in. It wasn't however until you were older that your interest in it cemented, though not in a way your parents expected.

Since then your faith has grown deeper and with it your passion both for magic and life. While others in your family have since gone on to become great mages, you yourself have chosen a different path. 

Instead you have chosen to become a Knight of the Mystic Fire, the sword arm of those who seek to maintain the Weave's stability. Mystra herself often relies upon followers to handle sources of potential instability, wherever they may be found. This requires a life of duty and hardship, one which you have since gladly accepted to be in service of your god.

It therefore was not surprising when you found yourself summoned by the high priest of your temple. Rumours of sorcerers powerful enough to tremble mountains, wizards who challenge the divide between worlds, and wild mages who ignore the Weave entirely have come through messengers to your temples doorstep. While these rumours perhaps may be nothing the high priest of your order has decided nevertheless to send you to investigate them. You now travel to Icewind Dale, staff in hand, ready to pit yourself against whatever magic is thrown in your way.~
@119=~Paladin who has Mystra to back him up~


@120=~Magic Missile~
@121=~Magic Missile
(Evocation)

Level: 1
Range: Visual range of the caster
Duration: Instant
Casting Time: 1
Area of Effect: 1 creature
Saving Throw: None

Casting Magic Missile, one of the most popular 1st-level spells, creates up to five missiles of magical energy that dart forth from the paladin's fingertips and unerringly strike their target, which must be a creature of some sort. Each missile inflicts 1d4+1 points of damage. For every two extra levels of experience after level 6, the paladin gains an additional missile<PRO_HESHE> has two at 8th level, three at 10th level, four at 12th level, and a maximum of five missiles at 14th level.~

@122=~Minor Sequencer~
@123=~Minor Sequencer
(Invocation/Evocation)

Level: 4
Range: 0
Duration: Permanent until activated
Casting Time: 9
Area of Effect: Special
Saving Throw: None

This spell allows the paladin to store two spells and activate them both at the same time from <PRO_HISHER> Special Abilities menu. Both spells must be of 2nd level or lower. To create a sequencer, the paladin must memorize not only Minor Sequencer but the spells <PRO_HESHE> intends to store in it. After casting Minor Sequencer, the player will be prompted to choose the sequenced spells from those <PRO_HESHE> has memorized.

A sequencer lasts until activated and, once used, releases its spells immediately (no casting time). The Special Abilities icon also disappears until the next time a sequencer is formed. The paladin can possess only one Minor Sequencer at a time, and it cannot be given to other characters.~



// Walker of the Forest (Divinate of Mielikki)
@124=~walker of the forest~
@125=~Walker of the Forest~
@126=~WALKER OF THE FOREST: Those who serve Mielikki typically are Druids, Rangers, or Clerics. However, despite her limited power she does maintain a small number of paladin followers. Though all her followers are known to be walkers of the forest, her paladins are rare in number to be noteworthy. These soldiers collectively train extensively against the challenges that would otherwise impede most travelers in the wild and as a result they are immune to most natural impediments. Though limited in what she can grant them Mielikki also has seen to grant her paladins access to a few additional spells.

Advantages:

- Level 1: Immune to Entangle and Web.
- Level 9: Becomes immune to Spike Growth.
- Can cast Entangle at level 6 (1st level), Web at level 9 (2nd level), and Summon Insects at level 12 (3rd level) out of your priest spellbook.

Disadvantages:

- Cannot cast Animate Dead or Slay Living 
- Does not benefit from Divine Courage

Restrictions:
May be Lawful Good, Neutral Good, Chaotic Good, or True Neutral.~

@127=~Those who serve Mielekki often find themselves being sent across the realms with the aim of protecting nature from acts of savagery. As one of her paladins you continue to strive to spread good in the world, teaching in the process the value of nature even in the harshest climates.

Though admittedly it is unusual that a paladin would take Mielekki as a patron, especially given that most who serve the Lady of the Forest are Rangers, Druids, or Clerics, you have always found yourself attached to her more than any of the other nature gods. Above all else you value nature, though you still personally place enough importance in civilization and formal church structure to never have favoured becoming a ranger yourself. As it stands your temple has only a small number of regular worshipers, though in time you hope to see this change.

What has most recently concerned you is the many tales of strife and death found in the north. Goblins, orcs, and bugbear raids are becoming increasingly prevalent, and you have asked the head of your temple for permission to travel to these distant lands to rid them of these menaces.

With civilization in the north gradually expanding you have also sensed an opportunity to spread to the towns and villages that make up Icewind Dale the value in the worship of Mielekki. For too long the inhabitants of the north have lived in constant fear of Auril and Talos, and it is your hope that you can render assistance for them with what little you have to offer. Mielekki is not by any means a powerful god, but what little she has granted you will have to do on this journey. Weapon in hand you travel for the small fishing village of Easthaven with the hope of spreading a positive message to a beleaguered people.~

@128=~A well trained paladin who watches over nature and follows Mielekki~



//Holy Warrior of Suffering     (ilmater)

@129=~holy warrior of suffering~
@130=~Holy Warrior of Suffering~
@131=~HOLY WARRIOR OF SUFFERING: Holy Warriors of Suffering are widely known for their willingness to put themselves in harms way to protect the downtrodden, the poor, and those who suffer. Though they are most often found living among the poorer denizens of Faerun's cities they can be found any place in the realms where there is suffering.


Advantages:

- Level 1: Gets +4 to saving throws vs death.
- Level 1: Gains an additional casting of Lay on Hands.
- Level 5: Can cast Favor of Ilmater once per day.
- Level 7: Can cast Champion's Strength once per day.
- Level 9: Can cast Entropy Shield once per day.


Disadvantages:

- Cannot cast Detect Evil or Smite Evil.
- Is not granted Divine Courage.


Restrictions:

- Must be Lawful Good, Neutral Good, Chaotic Good, or Lawful Neutral.~

@132=~The need you feel to assist others in suffering comes as much from your own experiences in life as it does from your respect for Ilmater. As a child your village faced frequent raids by bandits, mainly those looking for gold jewelry and other trinkets. In the eyes of your fellow villagers you saw the despair, loss of hope, and devastation that you now work to stop.

Until only a few days ago you resided in the Thentia, a city found along the northern coasts of the Moonsea. Though not nearly the size of Baldur's Gate or Waterdeep it is a city that still has its fair share of problems. Helping the sick, feeding and clothing the poor, and assisting the displaced are tasks that you and your order have often assisted in, particularly in the last few decades following the rise of Manshoon and the Zhentarim. Many of those who are least fortunate have been making their way east away from Zhentil's Keep, and Thentia can scarcely hold them all.

Though you are a young paladin your efforts in the city have not gone unnoticed. You were recently called before the head of your order.

The grand master of your order complimented you on your efforts in the city. Apparently, however, your order has received word of problems in Icewind Dale, a region far removed from the troubles that now plague Thentia. For reasons you don't quite understand your master has tasked you to travel there, stating that he believed that your presence could be of great benefit to relieving suffering in the region. 

Considering that the messages your temple has received are vague and sometimes even cryptic, simply saying in some cases that troubles are brewing, you have a degree of skepticism about your mission. With that in mind you have accepted your duty to help any in need and you travel light on your way to Icewind Dale.~
@133=~A well trained paladin who watches over the suffering and serves Ilmater~

@134=~Favor of Ilmater~
@135=~Favor of Ilmater
(Necromancy)

Level: 3
Sphere: Necromantic, Protection
Range: 30 ft.
Duration: Instant
Casting Time: 1
Area of Effect: 1 creature
Saving Throw: None

By invoking this spell, the caster switches <PRO_HISHER> own life force with that of the recipient, exchanging all physical injuries. The spell will only function if the caster has more Hit Points than the target before the switch is attempted. This switch is permanent until the caster uses normal methods to heal the damage. The exchange can be done from a distance so long as the spell range is not exceeded. Only the Hit Points are exchanged; the caster cannot take on other conditions from the target such as disease, poison, intoxication, and similar afflictions. 

This spell can only be cast by non-evil characters. It has no effect on undead, constructs, or extraplanar creatures.~


@136=~Entropy Shield~
@137=~Entropy Shield
(Abjuration)

Level: 6
Sphere: Protection
Range: 0
Duration: 1 round/level
Casting Time: 1
Area of Effect: The caster
Saving Throw: None

When cast, this spell surrounds the caster with a defensive maelstrom of energy that blocks or deflects many attacks. This gives the paladin a +6 bonus to Armor Class, a +2 bonus to Saving Throws, and +50% resistance to electricity, fire, cold, and acid. The paladin is also immune to Flamestrike and all missile-based attacks, including missiles created by spells such as Magic Missile.~

//Hivemaster

@138=~hivemaster~
@139=~Hivemaster~
@140=~HIVEMASTER: The Hivemaster druid lives to foster Insectoid and Arachnid life wherever it exists. The approach a druid takes in this regard can vary considerably and many consider them to be enigmatic. Still, Hivemasters have an unusual affinity towards insects that changes their approach to any given battle.

Advantages: 

- Level 1: Has immunity to poison.
- Level 9: Gains immunity to Web
- Learns (and therefore can memorize) Summon Insects, Giant Insect, Insect Plague, and Creeping Doom as though you were three levels higher as a druid. This means that you can cast Summon Insects as a 1st level spell once you hit level 2, you can cast Giant Insect as a 2nd level spell once you hit level 4, you can cast Insect Plague as a 3rd level spell once you hit level 6, and you can cast Creeping Doom as a 6th level spell once you hit level 11. You cannot however cast them at their normal level.

Disadvantages:

- Can only shapeshift into a Boring Beetle.
- Cannot wear greater than leather armor.~

@141=~You spent much of your childhood outdoors; scurrying about in the dirt, picking up various insects, and largely living a life as far removed from the civilized surroundings you found yourself in as much as possible. The bustling city of Waterdeep however was no place for those looking to commune with nature, a fact that became increasingly apparent to you as you became older. As you grew older you increasingly found yourself interested in the thought of leaving the city in order to study the worlds wonders on your own. From this it was only a natural progression that you would shortly thereafter find yourself as an initiate in a druid grove.

Though the study and protection of nature as a whole interests you, and you value the importance of preserving the balance, in your time as a member of your druid circle you've gained particular affinity for working with insects. Not only has this has significantly affected your spellcasting and strategy, it has also affected your worldview and your interest in seeing more of the wider world and what it has to offer. 

Not surprisingly, there are times when being an initiate in a small grove near the Misty Forest comes across as being rather limiting. The other druids in your grove don't quite have the passion that you have for insects, and there are times when you wish you were experienced enough to found your own grove. This hasn't stopped you from trying to read nearly every insect related book you could find, hoping to expand your knowledge and understanding in the process. 

A few months ago tales began spreading to your druid grove of trouble brewing in the north. At the time your druid grove's elders were reluctant to become involved, especially given what little was really known. However, a recent discovery by you of a large nest of rare Northern Horned Beetles near your grove has peaked your interest in the region. Normally these beetles stay within the icy caverns of the Spine of the World and seeing them appear this far south has made you concerned about the status of the balance in the region. In a passionate speech you explained to your druid elders that whatever was driving them south must be stopped. Having since obtained their permission you now travel northward to investigate these troubles yourself.~

@142=~A druid that likes insects more than most druids~

