//Leaftender kit
@34=~leaftender~
@35=~Leaftender~
@36=~LEAFTENDER: The Leaftender is similar in many ways to the druid--he or she is a priest who lives in and watches over the wild places that are so important to the halfling race. Despite the fact that his or her home and burrow is located deep in the woods, the Leaftender is not antisocial--halfling visitors will always find a warm welcome and be invited in to share a cup of a tea, a bit of conversation, and a warm fire.

The Leaftender works to slowly tame a forest without destroying it. He or she will plant nut trees and berry bushes to provide more food for the local wildlife, tend sick trees, and generally make the woods he or she dwells in a healthier, friendlier place.


Advantages:
- Has minor access to plant and animal spells. Plant spells include Entangle (1st), Shillelagh (1st), Barkskin (2nd), Goodberry (2nd), Spike Growth (3rd), Mold Touch (3rd), and Thorn Spray (4th). Animal spells include Charm Person or Mammal (2nd), Hold Animal (3rd), Summon Insect (3rd), Animal Summoning I, Call Woodland Beings, and Giant Insect.
- Level 2: They become immune to entangle
- Level 5: They become immune to charm magic


Disadvantages:
- He can only become proficient in clubs, quarterstaves, slings, and any of the weapon styles.
- Loses access to Animate Dead, Slay Living, and Finger of Death.

Restrictions:

- Must be a halfling
- Must be neutral or good alignments (you get spell access based on your alignment).
- Must have at least 9 charisma.~

@37=~Living on the outskirts of a remote Halfling village for most of your life youve grown accustomed to tending to a forests needs. So far this has namely involved curing sickly trees and planting nuts and berries, as well as caring for the odd sick wolf or deer that you encounter.

Your passion for nature knows no bounds however, and having read at a young age about the great trees of the north you have long wished to travel there to study them yourself. You also hope to bring plant life back to a region you hear has long since suffered from frost and cold.

Unfortunately, you live near a very active village where a local cleric is a necessity. Healing the odd burn or bruise, helping farmers facing drought or pestilence, and even teaching local children about the importance of nature have long since taken up too much of your time for any sort of serious traveling. 

Your time as a protector of nature and village healer did however leave you with a few connections within temples dedicated to preserving nature that could be reaching in only a few days travel. By chance you were able to arrange that a novice cleric of Mielikki take up the task of caring for your villages residents and forests, at least until you return. With the Elder Councils permission you have set out for Icewind Dale, staff in hand.~


@38=~LEAFTENDER: Its a cleric that shares many similarities to lower level druids~




//Priest of Luthic portion
@39=~priest of luthic~
@40=~Priest of Luthic~
@41=~PRIEST OF LUTHIC: Those who serve the Cave Mother know her to be wise but firm in her beliefs. Amongst her clergy there is a strong sense of connection to the earth as well as a value placed in the practice of minor healing. Of those in the Orc Pantheon she is the only one who has placed any interest in the art of healing, a view that her followers have noted. As a result in the midst of battle her followers can often be found on the front lines caring for the wounded, and, in rare cases, raising the fallen.


Advantages:

- Unlike other evil priests they gets access to all healing spells and healing-related necromancy spells (this includes Cure Critical Wounds, Mass Cure Light Wounds, Raise Dead, Heal, Greater Restoration, Regeneration, and Resurrection).
- They can also cast Blistering Disease as a 4th level spell. Its description is as follows.


Blistering Disease

Sphere: Necromancy 
Range: Touch
Duration: 8 rounds
Area of Effect: Single target
Casting Time: 4
Saving Throw: Save vs death

This spell afflicts one creature the priest targets with a disease that saps the target of 5 points of Strength. The bursting of blisters on the victim inflicts an additional 5 poison damage/ round for 8 rounds. A successful Save vs. negates all effects. This spell has no effect on undead, constructs, or extraplanar creatures. 



Disadvantages:

- Loses access to spells in the "Combat" sphere above level 4. This includes Righteous Magic, Righteous Wrath of the Faithful, Flame Strike, Slay Living, Bolt of Glory, and Unholy Word.

Restrictions:

- Must be evil.
- Must be a half-orc.~

//Biography
@42=~In your time as a priest of Luthic youve seen many battles, though mostly only from the sidelines. Caring for the injured is what you do best, even though this skill is often not appreciated by others of your kind. That said, when battle beckons you are well trained to answer it. In your time training as a priest you have become extremely proficient in your weapon of choice, something that is shared by many worshipers of Luthic.

Youve spent much of your life in the north, though only now have you truly had the chance to independently travel it. Less than a fortnight ago you were summoned by a high priest of Luthic. They saw your potential in battle and tasked you with travelling elsewhere in the north to gain strength and assist others as you see fit. Many in the north view Luthic as nothing more than servant of Gruumsh, and you are tasked with showing them otherwise.

Inspired by your own peoples tales of the region youve set out for Icewind Dale. In time you hope to eventually test yourself against the frozen tundra and mountains of the Spine of the World, where not even roaming packs of Yetis will stand in your way. ~

